Random Subsetting and Probability Distributions

#grab the ant data 
data <- read.csv("antcountydata.csv", header = TRUE, sep=",", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
littleData <- data[1:8, 3:6]

#running sample function with an integer
sample(10)
##  [1] 10  5  4  1  9  7  6  3  8  2
#applied to a vector, it randomizes the order of the elements
print(littleData$n.species)
## [1] 15 50 62 36 63 42 59 32
sample(littleData$n.species)
## [1] 42 32 36 59 15 50 63 62
sample(x=littleData$n.species,size=3)
## [1] 62 50 42
#sample with replacement for bootstrapping

sample(x=littleData$n.species,size=20, replace = TRUE)
##  [1] 50 63 32 50 62 42 32 42 50 62 36 50 36 42 63 63 32 50 15 63
#sample sizes must match
#sample(x=littleData$n.species,size=20, replace = FALSE) #doesn't work because longer than the vector

#null model analysis --> how communities are assembled

#suppose elements are not sample equiprobably
#community assembly and null models  (chosen with equal chance vs. unequal chance)

mainlandSpecies <- paste("Species", 1:10, sep="")
popSizes <- c(1000,500,100,20,10,5,5,5,1,1)

#equiprobable colonization of an island 
islandA <- sample(x=mainlandSpecies, size=5)
print(islandA)
## [1] "Species4"  "Species1"  "Species9"  "Species10" "Species6"
#assume colonization potential is proportional to population size 
islandB <- sample(x=mainlandSpecies, size=5, prob = popSizes) #must be same lengths/ no negative numbers
print(islandB)
## [1] "Species1" "Species2" "Species4" "Species3" "Species5"
#colonization now of individuals, not species
islandC <- sample(x=mainlandSpecies, size=100, prob = popSizes, replace=TRUE)
head(islandC)
## [1] "Species1" "Species1" "Species1" "Species2" "Species3" "Species2"
table(islandC)
## islandC
## Species1 Species2 Species3 Species5 Species8 
##       64       23       11        1        1
unique(islandC)
## [1] "Species1" "Species2" "Species3" "Species5" "Species8"
length(unique(islandC))
## [1] 5
#colonization of equiprobable individuals 

islandD <- sample(x=mainlandSpecies, size=100, prob = NULL, replace=TRUE)
head(islandD)
## [1] "Species6"  "Species1"  "Species2"  "Species5"  "Species9"  "Species10"
table(islandD)
## islandD
##  Species1 Species10  Species2  Species3  Species4  Species5  Species6 
##         9         7        12         8         8        10        14 
##  Species7  Species8  Species9 
##        15         7        10
unique(islandD)
##  [1] "Species6"  "Species1"  "Species2"  "Species5"  "Species9" 
##  [6] "Species10" "Species7"  "Species3"  "Species4"  "Species8"
length(unique(islandD))
## [1] 10
length(table(islandD) [table(islandD)>9]) #use logical operator to sort vector 
## [1] 5

#proability distributions 
#poisson distirbution
#"d" function gives the probability density

MyVec <- dpois(x=seq(0,10), lambda = 1) #lambda is a rate parameter; rate at which individual event is occuring 
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec) #discrete event counted in integer units; lambda controls probability mass (which is closer to 0 and then decreases...)

#poisson is good for rare events

MyVec <- dpois(x=seq(0,10), lambda = 2)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec)

MyVec <- dpois(x=seq(0,10), lambda = 5) #as you increase the level of lambda, it looks more like a normal distribution (for a discrete variable)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec)

#more rare event; 90% of time is a 0 
MyVec <- dpois(x=seq(0,10), lambda = 0.1)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec)

#truncated poisson where you eliminate 0 column because you can't observe 0 of something in nature

MyVec <- dpois(x=seq(0,10), lambda = 2)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec)

print(MyVec)  
##            0            1            2            3            4 
## 1.353353e-01 2.706706e-01 2.706706e-01 1.804470e-01 9.022352e-02 
##            5            6            7            8            9 
## 3.608941e-02 1.202980e-02 3.437087e-03 8.592716e-04 1.909493e-04 
##           10 
## 3.818985e-05
sum(MyVec) #shows probability density for each value; sum to very close to 1.0 --> determines height
## [1] 0.9999917
MyVec <- ppois(q=seq(0,10), lambda = 2) #change x to q for quantile 
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec)

#cumulative distribution function for the d plot from before 
#represents the tail probabilty for each of the numbers 

#inverse or q function
qpois(p=c(0.025, 0.975), lambda=50) #represents 95% of the data; p5% confidence interval 
## [1] 37 64
#means that 95% of items from distributions will fall between 37 and 64

x <- rpois(n=1000, lambda = 1.1) 

hist(x) #actual counts of distribution of data; this is the most commonly used function for these distributions

#binomial distribution (like for a coin flip)
#parameters --> 
#p= probability of dichotomous outcome
#size = number of trials that are possible 
#x = number of possible outcomes (set x equal to size for all of the possibilities)

MyVec <- dbinom(x=seq(0,10), size = 10, p=0.5)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec)

#biased coin
MyVec <- dbinom(x=seq(0,10), size = 10, p=0.75)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,10)
barplot(height = MyVec)

#how you detect supiscios coin

qbinom(p=c(0.025, 0.975), size = 100, prob=0.75)
## [1] 66 83
#expect to see majority between 66 and 83 times 

# Continued 02/28

#negative binomial: number of failures (values of MyVec) in a series of Bernouli trials (coin tossing) with probability of success p, before we reach a target number of successes 
# more heterogeneous (overdispersed) than a Poisson

MyVec <- dnbinom(x=seq(0,40),size=5,prob=0.5) #tails = failure 
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,40)
barplot(height=MyVec)

MyVec <- dnbinom(x=seq(0,40),size=1,prob=0.1)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,40)
barplot(height=MyVec)

#number of times we flipped coin before it was heads

#alternatively soecify mean - mu (represents mean/average of distribution
#size is a dispersion parameter 
#small values of size give overdispersion

MyVec <- dnbinom(x=seq(0,40),size=1,mu=5)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,40)
barplot(height=MyVec)

#distribution has mean of 5 in this example 

MyVec <- dnbinom(x=seq(0,40),size=10,mu=5)
names(MyVec) <- seq(0,40)
barplot(height=MyVec)

#distribution peaks at lower values and variance decreases; still have mean of 5
#this histogram is well described my this model; not a perfect example but gives an illustration; not literal mechanistic model; matches data well if you use the right set of parameters 

#pnbinom gives us the tail distribution 
pnbinom(q=3,size=1,mu=5) #what is the probability of getting 3 or smaller from this negative binomial distribution
## [1] 0.5177469
# = 50% will get 3,2,1 or 0

#qnorm for actual values for a p
qnbinom(p=0.05,size=10,mu=5) 
## [1] 1
#confidence interval
qnbinom(p=c(0.025, 0.975),prob=0.5,size=10) #number of failures between 3 and 20
## [1]  3 20
#random sample from negative binomial 
MyVec <- rnbinom(n=1000,size=1,mu=20)
quantile(MyVec,prob=c(0.025,0.975))
##  2.5% 97.5% 
##     0    75
qnbinom(p=c(0.025,0.975),size=1,mu=20)
## [1]  0 75
MyVec <- rnbinom(n=100,size=1,mu=20) #smaller sample size; small size = large distribution- large size = smaller distribution
quantile(MyVec,prob=c(0.025,0.975))
##   2.5%  97.5% 
##  0.475 71.725
qnbinom(p=c(0.025,0.975),size=1,mu=20)
## [1]  0 75
#uniform distribution 
#parameters are for minimum and maximum values

limits <- seq(0,10,by=0.01)
z <- dunif(x=limits, min=0,max=5)
names(z) <- limits
plot(x=limits, y=z,type="l",xlim=c(0,10)) #all states are equiprobable/equally likely to occur

#punif for tail probability
limits <- seq(0,10,by=0.1)
z <- punif(q=limits,min=0,max=5)
names(z) <- limits 
plot(x=limits, y=z, type="l",xlim=c(0,10)) #integral of uniform distribution, increasing the area/probability as we look at the range

#qunif for quantiles
qunif(p=c(0.025,0.975),min=0,max=5) #2.5% on each side 
## [1] 0.125 4.875
#runif to generate data

hist(runif(n=1000,min=0,max=5)) #peaks and valleys depends on size of bins; hard to interpret hist distribution because of the plotting

#normal distribution

hist(rnorm(n=100,mean=100,sd=2))

#should in theory create prefect bell curve 
#depending on mean and variance, normal distribution is unbounded; infinitely goes past extremes 

MyVec<- rnorm(n=100,mean=2,sd=2)
hist(rnorm(n=100,mean=2,sd=2)) #negative values here....

summary(MyVec)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -2.56500 -0.07607  1.25300  1.40900  2.89200  7.70700
TossZeroes <- MyVec[MyVec>0]
hist(TossZeroes) #not normal, lost low end of tail

summary(TossZeroes)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1212  1.0470  1.8210  2.2630  3.3060  7.7070
#want a continuous distribution with no negative values --> 
#gamma distribution
#2 parameters: shape1 and shape2
#continuous, positive values

hist(rgamma(n=100,shape=1,scale=10))

#gamma with shape = 1 gives us an exponential with scale = mean
#set shape smaller = more extreme distribution near low end 
hist(rgamma(n=100,shape=0.1,scale=10))

#larger shape = more like normal distribution
hist(rgamma(n=100,shape=20,scale=1))

#mean from gamma distribution = shape*scale
#variance = shape*scale^2

#good for positive continuous values

#Beta distribution
#continuous, but bounded between 0 and 1 
#can measure probability, envrionmental gradient (scale to a relative way), etc.
#parameters; shape1 = number of successes + 1; shape2 = number of failures + 1 (i.e. heads and tails)

#shape1 = 1; shape 2 = 1; "no data" 

hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=1,shape2=1), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100))

#shape 1 = 2; shape 2 = 1; "1 head"

hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=2,shape2=1), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100)) #more bias on heads than tails even with just first data value 

#two tosses, 1 head and 1 tail
hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=2,shape2=2), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100)) #more uniform/symmetric but the peak is more towards the center (unbiased)

#two tosses both heads

hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=3,shape2=1), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100)) #steeper towards right

#more data equal counts
hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=20,shape2=20), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100)) #very close to being unbiased 

#more data unequal counts
hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=20,shape2=10), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100))

#shape parameters less than 1?
hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=0.2,shape2=0.4), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100)) #shape below 1 = u shaped distribution

#equal counts below 1
hist(rbeta(n=1000,shape1=0.4,shape2=0.4), breaks=seq(0,1,length=100))

#range of model parameters = a lot more to work with than just normal distribution
#simulate distributions of errors/uncertainty 
#shapes based on parameters 
#scientific intference = start with data, what is the best estimate of the parameters? 

#estimating parameters from data 
#maximum liklihood estimation
#maximize the probability of obtaining data we have given a set of parameters
#we can change the underlying parameters

library(MASS)
x <- rnorm(1000,mean=92.5,sd=2.5)
hist(x)

fitdistr(x,"normal")   #specify kind of distribution)
##       mean           sd     
##   92.54929141    2.43527749 
##  ( 0.07701024) ( 0.05445446)
mean(x)
## [1] 92.54929
sd(x)
## [1] 2.436496
#looking at 3 sets of parameters 
#1 = true values, 2 = ...

#but what should we use for continuous, positive values? gamma!
#what is best estimate for the 2 parameters of the gamma distribution?
z <- fitdistr(x, "gamma")
str(z) #have shape and rate parameters 
## List of 5
##  $ estimate: Named num [1:2] 1442.8 15.6
##   ..- attr(*, "names")= chr [1:2] "shape" "rate"
##  $ sd      : Named num [1:2] 64.446 0.696
##   ..- attr(*, "names")= chr [1:2] "shape" "rate"
##  $ vcov    : num [1:2, 1:2] 4153.284 44.876 44.876 0.485
##   ..- attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   .. ..$ : chr [1:2] "shape" "rate"
##   .. ..$ : chr [1:2] "shape" "rate"
##  $ loglik  : num -2309
##  $ n       : int 1000
##  - attr(*, "class")= chr "fitdistr"
#rate = 1/scale
#so here is the estimate of the mean of distribution
z$estimate[1]/z$estimate[2]
##    shape 
## 92.54929
#estimate of variance 
z$estimate[1]/z$estimate[2]^2
##    shape 
## 5.936513
